1
00:00:00,650 --> 00:00:02,120
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,340 --> 00:00:16,660
Today I'll show you an interesting tool that lets you check what frequency to tune our Tesla to relative to the grenade.

3
00:00:18,220 --> 00:00:24,300
Because this frequency can't be determined with a signal generator.

4
00:00:25,060 --> 00:00:38,920
For example, if we hook the signal generator's probe to this antenna and sweep the frequency, we won't see this moment.

5
00:00:39,700 --> 00:00:45,320
We won't see it because this coil needs to be tested under load.

6
00:00:45,480 --> 00:00:53,880
Here you see we have the hot end of the coil, the cold end we start from, and the load hangs on it.

7
00:00:54,040 --> 00:01:00,720
For this test we're using a 15 W lamp.

8
00:01:02,420 --> 00:01:18,260
Lab signal generators of these types — these, higher-grade, various samples whoever has which — can't put out enough potential to really see how our coil responds to an electric field.

9
00:01:18,260 --> 00:01:25,040
To an electric field.

10
00:01:26,060 --> 00:01:28,380
The idea of this rig.

11
00:01:29,260 --> 00:01:37,840
I think many of you who've assembled coils and tuned them by frequency have some wire offcuts lying around.

12
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:44,280
They usually lie around as dead weight — sometimes we use them as jumpers, but generally they just sit there.

13
00:01:45,660 --> 00:01:51,100
Let's build this kind of rig from those pieces.

14
00:01:52,740 --> 00:01:58,640
This whole thing is assembled from offcuts of a single wire, because I cut a lot of it doing frequency tuning.

15
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:01,520
And it was kind of bugging me.

16
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:11,540
The spacing between taps is roughly 0.8 cm to 1.5 cm.

17
00:02:11,900 --> 00:02:14,440
Average spacing of about a centimeter.

18
00:02:14,540 --> 00:02:20,100
We make taps — about 20 — and fill the form.

19
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:30,420
The form is cardboard so we get a high Q-factor and a wider spectrum of frequencies we can catch.

20
00:02:30,440 --> 00:02:38,600
Winding direction — same as in this system and the working sample on the rig.

21
00:02:39,140 --> 00:02:44,680
The Tesla is wound to the left, that is counter-clockwise.

22
00:02:45,820 --> 00:03:00,980
Because there's a rule we all know — I'll repeat it once more — left-handed windings (counter-clockwise) are for the electric field, right-handed windings (clockwise) for the magnetic field.

23
00:03:00,980 --> 00:03:02,180
For the magnetic field.

24
00:03:03,160 --> 00:03:10,540
On this antenna we want to get electric potential, so we wind to the left.

25
00:03:11,780 --> 00:03:13,560
About 20 taps here.

26
00:03:13,900 --> 00:03:18,400
I gave the Kacher schematic in a previous video, so I won't dwell on it.

27
00:03:18,920 --> 00:03:22,480
The inductor is movable so we can slide it.

28
00:03:23,160 --> 00:03:29,080
And you can also see we've got an alligator clip — the wire goes to the transistor base.

29
00:03:29,800 --> 00:03:34,140
This lets us move along the wire.

30
00:03:35,960 --> 00:03:40,160
The movable inductor is for smooth frequency tuning.

31
00:03:40,980 --> 00:03:54,360
When we move between one tap and another, smooth tuning happens by slightly shifting the inductor left or right — this way you can tune the frequency.

32
00:03:54,940 --> 00:04:11,260
If we need to shift these frequencies down, we can put a ferrite rod — or whoever has them, a set of rings — into this rig and lower the frequencies.

33
00:04:11,260 --> 00:04:11,800
The frequencies.

34
00:04:12,240 --> 00:04:21,340
If we need the frequency to go higher, we can move along the taps.

35
00:04:22,300 --> 00:04:30,480
And if there's still not enough frequency, we reduce the number of turns or change the antenna's geometric dimensions.

36
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:35,880
The system ends up with a wide range.

37
00:04:36,040 --> 00:04:39,160
Before starting the system, connect the grounding.

38
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:55,340
The grounding should be exactly the one that'll be standard on the rig, because if we change the grounding later, the frequency will shift a bit within some limits for this coil.

39
00:04:56,520 --> 00:04:59,860
So you want to use exactly the working one.

40
00:04:59,900 --> 00:05:13,540
In this case here it's a 20 m cable — a wire connects to it, ending in an alligator clip that we'll connect to the coil taps.

41
00:05:14,020 --> 00:05:31,760
Turn on the oscilloscope, lay the probe about 15 cm away, so we can effectively track the coil's frequency and the electric field strength around the antenna.

42
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:34,720
Starting the system.

43
00:05:36,320 --> 00:05:40,000
Power will be from a lab signal generator.

44
00:05:40,840 --> 00:05:45,060
Supply voltage around 24 V.

45
00:05:45,140 --> 00:05:48,140
Standard for what they can be tuned to.

46
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:58,540
24 V and we're drawing a bit over an amp.

47
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:10,060
And here we see — the lamp lit up, we have an oscillogram, frequency 1 MHz and change.

48
00:06:10,540 --> 00:06:18,220
But before we start the test, we need to exclude the inductor's influence on this coil.

49
00:06:18,600 --> 00:06:25,620
Because the inductor sits between the antenna and the resonator, its influence has to be removed.

50
00:06:26,080 --> 00:06:35,500
You can see strong pickups on the inductor right now.

51
00:06:36,140 --> 00:06:38,100
How do we do that?

52
00:06:38,320 --> 00:06:43,560
You can use the capacitor that'll later be installed on the tank circuit.

53
00:06:44,100 --> 00:06:50,660
That's in the 0.1 µF to 1 µF range, selected.

54
00:06:52,320 --> 00:06:54,280
Or equivalent.

55
00:06:54,640 --> 00:06:56,540
Say, a particular capacitor.

56
00:06:57,230 --> 00:06:57,940
Connect it.

57
00:06:58,600 --> 00:06:59,480
High-voltage.

58
00:06:59,900 --> 00:07:03,180
You see the load doesn't light up.

59
00:07:03,280 --> 00:07:03,760
Remove it.

60
00:07:03,920 --> 00:07:04,800
It glows.

61
00:07:05,380 --> 00:07:09,500
But the best method is just to short out the inductor.

62
00:07:10,020 --> 00:07:11,140
Remove its influence.

63
00:07:11,380 --> 00:07:12,920
You can see the inductor's shorted.

64
00:07:13,640 --> 00:07:15,680
The load doesn't react at all.

65
00:07:16,240 --> 00:07:20,480
Next, we connect grounding to this coil.

66
00:07:21,720 --> 00:07:24,400
Connect it to the cold end.

67
00:07:26,360 --> 00:07:27,600
Grounding connected.

68
00:07:27,740 --> 00:07:31,720
You can see some glow appeared.

69
00:07:33,540 --> 00:07:36,600
We'll track that point.

70
00:07:38,180 --> 00:07:38,880
Look.

71
00:07:39,860 --> 00:07:42,380
This is the amplitude with grounding connected.

72
00:07:42,740 --> 00:07:43,800
The probe reacts.

73
00:07:44,340 --> 00:07:45,200
Disconnecting.

74
00:07:45,340 --> 00:07:46,560
You see the amplitude.

75
00:07:46,780 --> 00:07:55,280
Our goal is to find the frequency at which the electric field is maximally absorbed by this coil.

76
00:07:55,360 --> 00:07:57,740
That is, minimum amplitude on the oscilloscope.

77
00:07:57,860 --> 00:07:59,040
The probe stays put.

78
00:07:59,620 --> 00:08:04,740
You can also track this moment with the neon bulb.

79
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:10,080
Here — it starts glowing at about 18 cm away.

80
00:08:10,800 --> 00:08:21,300
Now, if I disconnect the grounding wire — glow at 40 cm from the antenna.

81
00:08:21,740 --> 00:08:24,740
So you can see the equivalent glow on the neon bulb.

82
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:30,220
Reconnect grounding and start the tuning transition.

83
00:08:31,680 --> 00:08:34,600
Starting to move along the taps.

84
00:08:36,400 --> 00:08:37,120
Moving.

85
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:38,780
Watch.

86
00:08:39,580 --> 00:08:40,840
First tap.

87
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:46,060
Connected — by the lamp glow.

88
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:48,920
Now let's move to, say, the fourth tap.

89
00:08:50,240 --> 00:08:51,080
Connected.

90
00:08:51,160 --> 00:08:52,140
Glow is brighter.

91
00:08:52,700 --> 00:08:59,180
So we reduce the amount of wire, the frequency goes up.

92
00:08:59,820 --> 00:09:00,820
And one more point.

93
00:09:01,420 --> 00:09:12,060
You want the antenna connected to the hot end — don't move the hot end, only move the ground point.

94
00:09:12,300 --> 00:09:25,920
Otherwise, if you try the opposite — say, we'd move the antenna connection — it would act as an additional radiator and introduce distortion.

95
00:09:26,460 --> 00:09:35,640
The signal should be a clean sine wave, no distortions.

96
00:09:35,740 --> 00:09:40,480
This is the most reliable method to make sure.

97
00:09:40,740 --> 00:09:47,640
You can also take the ends that are left unused, solder them and reconnect them back into the wire.

98
00:09:47,820 --> 00:09:50,360
That'll fully exclude any influence.

99
00:09:51,140 --> 00:10:00,700
So, next — the load glows, which means we can move the inductor a bit more, shift the board, and move further.

100
00:10:00,900 --> 00:10:04,320
Now switching gradually, watching the load.

101
00:10:06,220 --> 00:10:11,180
Switch to the fifth tap — glow grows.

102
00:10:11,720 --> 00:10:17,100
Sixth tap, seventh, eighth.

103
00:10:17,700 --> 00:10:19,920
You see the brightness rising.

104
00:10:20,960 --> 00:10:26,000
Ninth, tenth, eleventh.

105
00:10:26,580 --> 00:10:29,480
So we have a trend of the frequency rising.

106
00:10:30,640 --> 00:10:43,440
In this case, we can confirm the frequency is now a megahertz here on the antenna.

107
00:10:43,980 --> 00:10:46,300
And the load is glowing nicely.

108
00:10:46,440 --> 00:10:47,580
Testing further.

109
00:10:47,980 --> 00:10:58,100
Move the inductor — let's see if we can find a spot where the load glows even brighter.

110
00:10:59,720 --> 00:11:01,320
Moving by taps.

111
00:11:01,320 --> 00:11:07,060
Even brighter glow.

112
00:11:07,940 --> 00:11:11,060
Pretty bright here.

113
00:11:12,160 --> 00:11:19,900
Moving on — sixteenth tap out of twenty.

114
00:11:20,200 --> 00:11:22,040
Brightness is going down.

115
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:25,240
So we can stop.

116
00:11:26,960 --> 00:11:29,640
Fifteenth, sixteenth tap in this case.

117
00:11:31,400 --> 00:11:35,560
You see I went through the taps up to here.

118
00:11:37,780 --> 00:11:38,380
And now

119
00:11:42,020 --> 00:11:48,780
we can play with the inductor itself.

120
00:11:49,200 --> 00:11:51,040
Between the taps.

121
00:11:53,340 --> 00:11:58,540
Move the inductor and find the maximum glow on our load.

122
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:01,740
This is maximum glow.

123
00:12:02,420 --> 00:12:10,020
You can also note that consumption goes down when the system is well coordinated.

124
00:12:10,860 --> 00:12:18,620
For my coil, we found the optimal point where the system frequency comes in.

125
00:12:18,880 --> 00:12:19,900
Corresponds to

126
00:12:23,340 --> 00:12:26,220
1.135 MHz.

127
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:34,680
Next — you can add load visualization to this rig.

128
00:12:35,200 --> 00:12:40,600
You can add a rectifier here and hook up meters.

129
00:12:41,440 --> 00:12:57,640
For instance, you can put a voltmeter on this rig and instead of judging by eye how the lamp glows, track the moment when the voltmeter shows max voltage on the load.

130
00:12:57,780 --> 00:13:03,440
That'll match the frequency you need for this coil.

131
00:13:03,540 --> 00:13:19,560
Also, to nail down the result on the frequency response for this coil, I recommend after measurements with one antenna, connect another — fewer turns of wire, change the overall dimensions from the previous one — and check the frequency again.

132
00:13:19,560 --> 00:13:23,980
Compared to the previous and check the frequency too.

133
00:13:24,380 --> 00:13:32,920
And at that or another frequency on this antenna we'll see maximum absorption by our resonator.

134
00:13:33,840 --> 00:13:47,480
And yes — you can see I hung a much shorter antenna with much wider spacing and connected it to the system.

135
00:13:47,620 --> 00:14:01,360
Had to move to a lower tap, slide the inductor, the load glows equivalently and we can also confirm this frequency.

136
00:14:04,100 --> 00:14:18,680
You can play with this system at lower frequencies by adding ferrite — that is, this rig lets you take the full frequency response of the resonator.

137
00:14:21,320 --> 00:14:36,840
You can also play at higher frequencies — for that, instead of an antenna we connect a single equivalent turn to the hot end.

138
00:14:37,380 --> 00:14:38,820
And test the same way.

139
00:14:38,920 --> 00:14:43,600
You can slide it along the coil and look at the dependencies.

140
00:14:44,060 --> 00:14:46,200
Everyone makes their own setup.

141
00:14:46,500 --> 00:15:00,680
I recommend also adding a diode bridge, a filter, and a voltmeter here — so you can judge by voltage how precise your tuning is.

142
00:15:00,740 --> 00:15:16,500
We changed the antenna — let's also check this: when we move the grounding point between cold and hot end, our consumption shouldn't change too dramatically.

143
00:15:16,500 --> 00:15:29,540
Right now we have grounding on the cold end — let's check consumption, 24 V at 0.75 A. Move to the hot end —

144
00:15:33,070 --> 00:15:35,110
consumption went up a bit.

145
00:15:35,690 --> 00:15:56,150
That's normal — because when grounding is on the hot end, the turns that pick up the electric field from the antenna are closer to the surface of the case, so we get a small consumption increase.

146
00:15:56,150 --> 00:15:58,330
Increase in consumption.

147
00:15:58,750 --> 00:16:12,470
Overall we can see consumption changes insignificantly, which means this is the frequency that best fits this coil and is well coordinated with it.

148
00:16:13,730 --> 00:16:22,430
Moving on to questions that, in my view, are the most relevant and interesting.

149
00:16:23,650 --> 00:16:25,110
Question 1.

150
00:16:25,930 --> 00:16:33,910
Is there a dependence between the high-voltage coil's wire length and the resonator's wire length?

151
00:16:34,530 --> 00:16:46,870
The question is correct — there is of course some dependence in wave distribution. We wind the high-voltage coil to a wire length equal to the resonator's wire length.

152
00:16:47,010 --> 00:16:59,590
Or if our resonator requires a higher frequency, we wind the high-voltage coil to a wire length equal to half the resonator wire length.

153
00:17:00,430 --> 00:17:02,930
There's another interesting point.

154
00:17:03,110 --> 00:17:22,450
This thing we all hang on it, called the antenna — there's some dependency on the capacitance formed between its surface and the grounded coil, and that also affects frequency.

155
00:17:22,450 --> 00:17:23,010
The frequency.

156
00:17:23,610 --> 00:17:25,870
But it's not just about that.

157
00:17:26,350 --> 00:17:32,090
The wire length of this antenna must correspond

158
00:17:35,350 --> 00:17:41,250
to effective radiation at the frequency the high-voltage coil runs at.

159
00:17:41,430 --> 00:17:48,950
That is, antenna rules apply to these spiral resonators — they have to radiate effectively.

160
00:17:49,050 --> 00:17:54,450
That is, basically a quarter-wave radiator, or three-quarter, or five-quarter.

161
00:17:54,590 --> 00:17:58,830
That is, we fit it to something like that by length.

162
00:17:59,550 --> 00:18:06,850
The simplest method, of course, is fitting by cutting off conductor length.

163
00:18:07,990 --> 00:18:14,630
And aim for maximum electric field around the antenna.

164
00:18:14,690 --> 00:18:19,690
So that it can really work as an antenna.

165
00:18:21,270 --> 00:18:26,750
Again, at the frequency our Tesla creates.

166
00:18:28,190 --> 00:18:41,510
This is more about antenna theory — the wire has a physical length, a diameter, and it's also wound into a coil.

167
00:18:42,050 --> 00:18:48,370
For antennas you can calculate this, even on online calculators.

168
00:18:49,110 --> 00:19:04,290
And when it's mounted on the coil and tied to it through a capacitive coupling, and the coil is grounded — those calculations don't quite fit, in fact they're pretty far off.

169
00:19:04,310 --> 00:19:09,150
So we end up having to fit the wire length in practice.

170
00:19:10,470 --> 00:19:22,850
Since the high-voltage coil's conductor length is fixed for us, we end up tuning the frequency by changing the antenna's geometric dimensions.

171
00:19:23,330 --> 00:19:29,450
Compress, decompress its turns, increase the diameter — that is, manipulate it.

172
00:19:29,890 --> 00:19:46,630
And if we can't dial in the effective frequency we found with this rig, then we change the winding diameter of this wire at the length that should match the wire length in the coil.

173
00:19:48,690 --> 00:19:54,270
Change the form diameter — that'll also cause a frequency-response shift.

174
00:19:54,850 --> 00:20:05,090
Question 2 — where do the main processes happen: in the grenade itself or in its inductor?

175
00:20:05,990 --> 00:20:14,110
In most online builds people make, all the processes happen in the inductor.

176
00:20:14,830 --> 00:20:25,850
And relative to the inductor, the grenade itself is just a bunch of wire that the magnetic field acts on.

177
00:20:26,370 --> 00:20:36,470
The interaction happens between the antenna, the electric field from the Tesla, and the magnetic field in the inductor.

178
00:20:36,490 --> 00:20:39,790
And this coil is just a pickup.

179
00:20:40,450 --> 00:20:54,310
But that mode is very unstable — that's when we make a mediator, that is, we drive the inductor into resonator mode and just pick up.

180
00:20:54,430 --> 00:20:55,550
And the mode is inefficient.

181
00:20:55,670 --> 00:21:09,970
It's far more efficient to drive the main coil into resonator mode, and leave the inductor to act as the rotating magnetic field source — then all the processes happen in this coil.

182
00:21:10,090 --> 00:21:18,270
That's why we calculate per the program, wind to fit the right inductance and get all the processes in it.

183
00:21:20,330 --> 00:21:21,730
Question 3.

184
00:21:22,670 --> 00:21:34,810
In one of your videos — the push-pull frequency-search methodology — you showed that for your coil the frequency is 90.8 kHz.

185
00:21:35,530 --> 00:21:36,390
Why so high?

186
00:21:36,610 --> 00:21:38,430
Why is the frequency that high?

187
00:21:39,010 --> 00:21:47,710
After all, we all work at frequencies from 9 to 35 kHz and the LC tank circuit in our system works fine.

188
00:21:48,850 --> 00:21:55,190
In that video I showed the method for finding exactly the frequency needed for that coil.

189
00:21:55,330 --> 00:21:58,830
I didn't misspeak — that's exactly the frequency.

190
00:21:59,250 --> 00:22:00,310
What's happening?

191
00:22:00,310 --> 00:22:08,970
We've all seen this moment where you tune the LC tank to whatever frequency you happen to land on.

192
00:22:09,070 --> 00:22:13,010
Everyone tunes to whatever worked out.

193
00:22:13,070 --> 00:22:16,530
Pick a series capacitor and tune.

194
00:22:17,170 --> 00:22:21,270
That ends up being tuning to the first LC resonance harmonic.

195
00:22:21,610 --> 00:22:30,010
And when you connect a load, you see push-pull consumption drop in current.

196
00:22:32,410 --> 00:22:34,990
Everything's normal — we all know that moment.

197
00:22:35,450 --> 00:22:36,310
What's happening?

198
00:22:36,430 --> 00:22:38,230
Nothing supernatural.

199
00:22:38,790 --> 00:22:53,030
At the moment when the LC tank isn't loaded, to maintain max oscillation amplitude it needs a certain amount of electric energy.

200
00:22:53,430 --> 00:23:08,030
The moment we connect a load, we detune the tank — its frequency shifts off the main oscillation — and it turns out that for lower oscillation amplitude in the tank, less energy is also needed.

201
00:23:08,030 --> 00:23:10,230
A smaller amount of electric energy.

202
00:23:10,390 --> 00:23:15,990
That's exactly why you see push-pull consumption go down.

203
00:23:17,050 --> 00:23:18,630
What do we do?

204
00:23:18,830 --> 00:23:20,430
That's the wrong tuning.

205
00:23:21,790 --> 00:23:30,630
The inductor tank should be tuned to the third, fifth, seventh, or ninth harmonic — odd ones.

206
00:23:31,410 --> 00:23:36,070
In that case, what happens when you tune the push-pull to a harmonic?

207
00:23:37,600 --> 00:23:43,870
The tank detuning is insignificant, much less than at the first harmonic.

208
00:23:44,510 --> 00:23:56,630
If you tune it that way, you'll see at load connection on an odd harmonic, the push-pull consumption either doesn't change or actually rises.

209
00:23:57,210 --> 00:23:59,330
The tank becomes stable.

210
00:23:59,450 --> 00:24:06,850
And so we can, by tuning the inductor tank to a harmonic, hit the frequency we actually need.

211
00:24:07,310 --> 00:24:09,790
In this case, applied to my coil.

212
00:24:09,930 --> 00:24:14,230
For me the frequency should be 90.8 kHz.

213
00:24:14,810 --> 00:24:17,210
I tune to the fifth harmonic.

214
00:24:17,730 --> 00:24:23,590
For me, on the fifth harmonic, my push-pull should run at 18 kHz.

215
00:24:24,490 --> 00:24:30,050
That's 18 kHz plus another 0.1 kHz when you get precise tuning.

216
00:24:30,550 --> 00:24:36,930
So my push-pull runs like yours, at about 18.1 kHz.

217
00:24:38,030 --> 00:24:43,730
And the inductor tank circuit has a frequency of 90.8 kHz.

218
00:24:44,250 --> 00:24:48,930
Nothing supernatural — just running on a harmonic.

219
00:24:49,690 --> 00:24:58,050
You have to understand the electric field from the Tesla can't influence

220
00:25:02,450 --> 00:25:12,010
the magnetic field rotating in the inductor at the moment the push-pull fires.

221
00:25:12,110 --> 00:25:15,730
That is, we need to create free oscillations in the tank.

222
00:25:16,230 --> 00:25:24,270
You can compare it to a flywheel that we pushed and it spins a number of times on its own.

223
00:25:24,630 --> 00:25:41,090
Working with the Tesla via the magnetic field, during the free oscillations of the magnetic field — and therefore current movement too — is the only way our system can work.

224
00:25:41,430 --> 00:25:47,290
When we run at the first LC resonance harmonic, we won't get anything like this.

225
00:25:47,970 --> 00:25:52,450
So: third, fifth, seventh, or ninth harmonic.

226
00:25:52,530 --> 00:25:59,330
Don't go higher than the ninth — the Q-factor drops.

227
00:26:00,190 --> 00:26:00,670
Not worth it.

228
00:26:00,870 --> 00:26:02,170
Question 4.

229
00:26:03,170 --> 00:26:15,170
Info started appearing online about a TL-494 chip "glitch" that lets you bring this system to operating mode.

230
00:26:15,710 --> 00:26:18,070
Have you heard of this, and what is it?

231
00:26:20,710 --> 00:26:22,190
Let's analyze this process.

232
00:26:22,430 --> 00:26:40,850
Yes — people who manage to get gain out of these systems, or bring them to some operating mode, do use what's been called a "chip glitch."

233
00:26:41,570 --> 00:26:46,870
But in this case, there isn't actually a chip glitch.

234
00:26:47,590 --> 00:26:49,330
The process here is very simple.

235
00:26:50,490 --> 00:26:57,510
Feedback forms between the driving chip and the system.

236
00:26:58,370 --> 00:27:11,570
It forms when there's influence either on pin 3, most often pin 4, or on the frequency-setting pin 5 where the frequency-setting cap sits.

237
00:27:13,510 --> 00:27:24,830
Because this chip isn't shielded, and it sits near the antenna itself or near the Tesla high-voltage coil.

238
00:27:26,990 --> 00:27:28,810
Let's look at this in more detail.

239
00:27:28,890 --> 00:27:29,770
What happens?

240
00:27:29,930 --> 00:27:37,050
When the inductor's tank is running, we have a magnetic field.

241
00:27:38,230 --> 00:27:56,010
This magnetic field has a certain diameter around the system, and right above the inductor is the Tesla antenna, on which an electric field appears when we turn it on.

242
00:27:56,530 --> 00:28:04,690
The Tesla's electric field has a much bigger diameter, and chips can fall within its influence.

243
00:28:05,270 --> 00:28:07,390
And this interesting phenomenon happens.

244
00:28:08,210 --> 00:28:23,430
The magnetic field modulates the electric field, and since the Tesla's electric field has a big diameter, due to poor assembly or long wires you can get a pickup

245
00:28:23,650 --> 00:28:31,270
on pins 3, 4, or 5 of this chip.

246
00:28:31,810 --> 00:28:33,850
What can happen as a result?

247
00:28:34,250 --> 00:28:46,690
The chip's output duty cycle can change, the frequency can shift within some range, or it can stop working entirely.

248
00:28:48,390 --> 00:29:04,430
There's an unpleasant feature — with a duty cycle change, push-pull transistors can blow up, because the chip starts working erratically from strong pickup and the channels overlap.

249
00:29:04,430 --> 00:29:05,850
On the output duty cycle.

250
00:29:05,930 --> 00:29:07,530
This is what usually happens.

251
00:29:08,110 --> 00:29:12,590
But this effect can be used to our benefit in the system.

252
00:29:13,390 --> 00:29:14,410
How to do it?

253
00:29:14,590 --> 00:29:31,130
You have to understand that when we create clean sine oscillations in the inductor — they have the same amplitude, positive half-period equal in amplitude to the negative half-period —

254
00:29:31,130 --> 00:29:41,990
such harmonic oscillations, like direct current, are a normal phenomenon for the medium.

255
00:29:42,210 --> 00:29:54,930
For the medium, basically. And when there's magnetic field skew, various lengths that tune them, the system goes into imbalance, becomes asymmetric.

256
00:29:54,930 --> 00:29:55,650
Into an asymmetric system.

257
00:29:56,250 --> 00:30:05,550
This anomalous behavior is perceived by the medium as a major disturbance that needs to be suppressed.

258
00:30:05,710 --> 00:30:07,250
And it responds sharply.

259
00:30:07,390 --> 00:30:14,050
That's how people happen to catch this operating mode and see some gain.

260
00:30:14,610 --> 00:30:27,090
The gain will be significant — it can even lead the system into so-called self-running, when the system starts running itself.

261
00:30:27,210 --> 00:30:29,430
But this mode is very unstable.

262
00:30:29,530 --> 00:30:39,950
It's an uncontrolled process that often gets knocked off and leads to electronics failure in the system.

263
00:30:40,730 --> 00:30:46,090
You can use it, but I don't recommend it.

264
00:30:46,190 --> 00:30:49,350
The process needs to be made more controllable.

265
00:30:49,450 --> 00:30:55,490
The system really works like a living organism, so a complex setup is needed.

266
00:30:55,510 --> 00:31:05,670
For people earning on this principle — I repeat, the Tesla isn't working as it should for getting decent power.

267
00:31:05,810 --> 00:31:13,090
The whole system is uncoordinated and you won't get big powers out of it.

268
00:31:13,210 --> 00:31:20,490
Due to the skew of the magnetic and electric fields, you can see some gain in this system.

269
00:31:21,930 --> 00:31:23,510
Good luck to everyone with your experiments.

270
00:31:25,270 --> 00:31:26,050
All the best.
